<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06206038 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06206038 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HEALTH; FITNESS; LETTER; QA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Q Would you have any idea why my father would be told by his doctor not tohave coffee when he's chewing nicotine gum? My father has been a heavy smoker,and I finally got him to the point where he went for help. But if he has togive up cigarettes and coffee at the same time, I'm not sure that he's goingto make it. Could you give me some idea about what's going on here?; --Joshua, St. Augustine, Fla.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DRINKING COFFEE CANCELS VALUE OF NICOTINEGUM  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  AdviceHealth andamp; FitnessFamily PracticeNeil Solomon is a Maryland author and practicing physician with specialexpertise in diet and weight control.  </MEMO><TEXT>  A If you check more closely, you'll probably find that your father was toldnot to drink coffee while he's chewing nicotine gum; this does not mean thathe has to stop drinking coffee entirely. The reason is that acidic drinksprevent the active ingredient in the nicotine gum from entering thebloodstream. This is not only true of coffee, but of cola beverages as well.By drinking coffee while using the nicotine gum, your father is neutralizingits value.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Dr. Neil Solomon column  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910724  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  182  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday July 24, 199100206038,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>